---
import BaseLayout from "../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import Highlight from "../../components/Highlight.astro";
import HighlightCollection from "../../components/HighlightCollection.astro";
---

<BaseLayout>
  <h1>Ideal Elevator Experience</h1>
  <p>
    I was once given the task to design the ideal elevator experience, as part
    of a job interview. In this case study, I walk you through my user-centered
    design process for tackling such design challenges.
  </p>
  <h2><span>Step 1.</span> Research</h2>
  <p>
    My first step was to learn more about elevators and people’s experiences
    with them.
  </p>
  <HighlightCollection>
    <Highlight title="Interview users">
      I interviewed 9 people about their experiences with elevators. They
      mentioned 30 different things they disliked about them, such as social
      awkwardness and dirty, cramped interiors. However, waiting for the
      elevator was by far their biggest complaint.
    </Highlight>
    <Highlight title="Research Elevators">
      I read around 20 articles about elevators and learned many interesting
      things. For instance, it’s a myth that all close-door buttons don’t work.
      The main insight, though, was that elevator experts agree that waiting is
      the thing that people dislike most about elevators.
    </Highlight>
    <Highlight title="Research psychology of waiting">
      I read up on the psychology of waiting. I learned that many factors
      influence our perception of waiting time. For instance, waiting time seems
      longer when we don’t know how long it’ll be, what is causing it, or when
      it’s perceived as unfair.
    </Highlight>
  </HighlightCollection>
  <h2><span>Step 2.</span> Requirements & Constraints</h2>
  <p>
    I created extra requirements and constraints, to give the project a clearer
    focus.
  </p>
  <HighlightCollection>
    <Highlight title="Client">
      I interviewed 9 people about their experiences with elevators. They
      mentioned 30 different things they disliked about them, such as social
      awkwardness and dirty, cramped interiors. However, waiting for the
      elevator was by far their biggest complaint.
    </Highlight>

    <Highlight title="User groups">
      Residential elevators are used by different groups of people, such as
      guests of residents, janitors, and maintenance personnel. However, the
      main user group are residents. These can be people of any age and some may
      have sensory, motor, or other disabilities.
    </Highlight>
    <Highlight title="Physical and technical constraints">
      The elevator should work in luxury residential buildings with 4 to 12
      floors, in any country around the world, and use the "collective control"
      algorithm. In short, that means the elevator will only switch direction
      when requests to continue in the current direction have been exhausted.
    </Highlight>
  </HighlightCollection>

  <h2><span>Step 3.</span> Problem statement</h2>
  <p>
    I distilled my research, requirements and constraints into a concise problem
    statement.
  </p>
  <blockquote>
    Improve the elevator experience of residents of 4 to 12 story luxury
    apartment buildings by reducing perceived waiting time.
  </blockquote>
  <h2><span>Step 4.</span> Use Research Insights</h2>
  <p>
    I used what I had learned about elevators and the psychology of waiting, to
    come up with various features that would reduce perceived waiting time.
  </p>
  <HighlightCollection>
    <Highlight title="Speed">
      The elevator will travel up at 83 km/h (above which people get sick) and
      down at 36 km/h (above which people experience the sensation of falling).
      This will reduce both actual and perceived waiting time.
    </Highlight>
    <Highlight title="Mirrors">
      The shaft doors will feature mirrors. Occupied time feels shorter and
      people have a natural tendency to check their personal appearance. This is
      one of the oldest tricks to reduce perceived elevator waiting time.
    </Highlight>
    <Highlight title="Time">
      Computer screens will be installed behind the semi-transparent mirrors on
      the shaft doors. One door will display the current time, since people
      overestimate waiting time and clocks counteract this tendency.
    </Highlight>
    <Highlight title="Weather">
      Weather information will be shown on the other shaft door. This can be
      effective, since residents may be on their way out and information
      relevant to a waiting setting reduces perceived waiting time. It may also
      start conversations, which enhances the feeling of being part of a group,
      and waiting in a group feels shorter than waiting alone.
    </Highlight>
    <Highlight title="Color">
      Warm colors increase perceived waiting time, while cool colors have the
      opposite effect. Therefore, the waiting area will be painted in a cool
      color, such as blue.
    </Highlight>
    <Highlight title="Light">
      High light levels increase perceived waiting time, while low light levels
      have the opposite effect. Therefore, the waiting area will be dimly lit.
    </Highlight>
    <Highlight title="Scent">
      Certain fragrances, such as lavender and nutmeg, have been found to reduce
      anxiety and anxiety increases perceived waiting time. Therefore, a scent
      diffuser will emit a low-concentration blend of such fragrances.
    </Highlight>
    <Highlight title="Accessibility">
      The call buttons will be placed low enough for people in wheelchairs (and
      children) to reach them. They will also give tactile feedback and feature
      braille to facilitate use by visually impaired people. Lastly, a voice UI
      will announce the current floor, the location of the elevator, the
      direction in which it is traveling, and at which floors it is going to
      stop.
    </Highlight>
  </HighlightCollection>
  <h2><span>Step 5.</span> Explore Visual UI Concepts</h2>
  <p>
    The elevator will also feature a visual UI. This UI will communicate the
    same information as the voice UI to sighted and hearing impaired residents.
    Perceived waiting time will be reduced, since the UI will explain why the
    elevator has not yet arrived at the current floor.
  </p>
  <p>
    I sketched various concepts to explore both what to show and how to show it.
    This made me more aware of the choices I had to make, such as the ones shown
    here.
  </p>
  <HighlightCollection>
    <Highlight title="Orientation">
      Should the UI be vertical or horizontal? Vertical matches the elevator’s
      axis of movement. However, a horizontal UI can be placed above the
      elevator doors, which enhances visibility.
    </Highlight>
    <Highlight title="Floor indicator">
      Should floors be indicated with numbers or shapes? Numbers are more
      informative, but can lead to cultural challenges. For instance, some
      countries use 0 for the ground floor, while others use 1. Also, some
      countries don’t use certain “unlucky” floor numbers.
    </Highlight>
    <Highlight title="Cause of stop">
      Should the UI show whether stops are due to passenger pickup or drop off?
      Waiting time is perceived as shorter, when people know the cause. On the
      other hand, this information might create excessive visual clutter.
    </Highlight>
  </HighlightCollection>

  <h2><span>Step 6.</span> Create Hi-Fi Mockups</h2>
  <p>
    I created various iterations of high-fidelity mockups, after having settled
    on only showing:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>The floor the user is on</li>
    <li>The floor the elevator is on</li>
    <li>The floors the elevator will stop on</li>
    <li>The direction of the elevator</li>
  </ul>
  <h2><span>Step 7.</span> User Tests and Iteration</h2>
  <p>
    I tested two high-fidelity mockups with users and iterated based on the test
    results.
  </p>
  <h3>First round</h3>
  <p>
    I showed the 2 concepts below to 3 participants. I asked them which floor
    the elevator was on, whether the elevator was going up or down, where the
    elevator was going to stop, and which floor they themselves were on. The top
    concept was easier to understand, but the elevator’s direction and
    participants’ floor were not clear to all.
  </p>
  <h3>Second round</h3>
  <p>
    To address these issues, I created the new concept shown below. I performed
    the same user test with 4 new participants. This time, the elevator’s
    direction was obvious to all participants. It was still not clear to
    everyone which floor they were on, though. A different visual indicator and
    a floor number sign next to the elevator might resolve this issue.
  </p>
  <h2><span>Step 8.</span> Final Result</h2>
  <p>
    I combined the findings and insights from my research into the following
    recommended features:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>High speed elevator</li>
    <li>Semi-transparent mirrors</li>
    <li>Weather info on mirror doors</li>
    <li>Display time on mirror doors</li>
    <li>Cool paint color in waiting area</li>
    <li>Dim lighting in waiting area</li>
    <li>Anxiety-reducing fragrances</li>
    <li>Low placed braille buttons</li>
    <li>Voice UI</li>
    <li>Semi-transparent mirrors</li>
  </ul>
</BaseLayout>
